frameDefinitions: A person (the Cognizer) comes to believe something (the Content), sometimes after a process of reasoning.
A Host is judged regarding their attitude as a potential host in a guest-host relationship.
Two (or more) people (the Parties, also encodable as Party_1 and Party_2) come to an agreement committing them to carrying out an Obligation.
Two (or more) people (the Parties, also encodable as Party_1 and Party_2) have an agreement.
Two (or more) people (the Parties, also encodable as Party_1 and Party_2) negotiate an agreement.
A Cognizer makes a Decision, which may be about an entity or a course of action.
frameExamples: Based on the most recent census I have <t>concluded</t> that most Americans sleep too much.
I found the board to be very <t>hospitable</t> to Russian graduates.
No arms <t>compromise</t> between the two parties is expected before the end of 2012.
The US and Russia have an <t>agreement</t> to share early warning data on missile launches.
So far , we have <t>agreed</t>to cede 100km of coastline to Kiribati . DNI
listRoleDefinitions: Cognizer is the person who comes to believe something.
Words in this frame may occur with a PP headed by <ment>from</ment> which expresses the Evidence on which knowledge or belief is based:
With a target verb, the Content is usually expressed as a finite clausal Complement or an Object NP, and may sometimes be expressed by a PP:

Some verbs in this frame may occur with postverbal Topic expressions: They <t>found out</t> <fex name='Topic'>about us</fex>! More generally verbs in this frame may occur with quantificational nouns followed by Topic expressions:
An act performed by the <fen>Cognizer</fen> which enables them to figure something out.
<fen>Medium</fen> is the text created by the <fen>Cognizer</fen> to communicate that they came to believe a specified <fen>Content</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> discovers the <fen>Content</fen>.
The location at which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> realizes the <fen>Content</fen>.
The <fen>Host</fen> is the person whose <fen>Behavior</fen> towards others as a (potential) host is evaluated.
The <fen>Guest</fen> is the entity which is positively or negatively treated by the <fen>Host</fen>.
The <fen>Behavior</fen> is the action of the <fen>Host</fen> on which the evaluation of the <fen>Host</fen>'s character is based.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the situation or person that the <fen>Host</fen>'s <fen>Behavior</fen> responds to or is related to.
The <fen>Expressor</fen> is the body part or action by a body part which indicates the character of the <fen>Host</fen>.
The individual whose point of view is taken in assigning the evaluation.

The individual or individuals that form the more prominent (i.e., agentive) party to the compromise, as compared with <fen>Party_2</fen>. That is, <fen>Party_1</fen> is generally encoded as the External Argument of verbs, and peripheral FEs that do not make reference to the event itself generally make reference to <fen>Party_1</fen>. Thus <fen>Manner</fen> is construed to be that of <fen>Party_1</fen>, not necessarily that of <fen>Party_2</fen> or the group of <fen>Parties</fen> as a whole.
The semantically (and grammatically) less prominent participant (or group of participants) in the compromise. It is generally encoded within a prepositional phrase (e.g. headed by <m>with</m>).
An expression of the commitment made by the <fen>Parties</fen> .
<fen>Topic</fen> is a description of the domain covered by the compromise.
The group of individuals portrayed as equally involved in reaching a compromise.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the compromise occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the compromise occurs.
